\f1\fs32\b CHAPTER 4\par\par
ALGORITHM\b0\fs24\f0\par\par
\f1\fs28\b 4.1 Introduction\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 Algorithms form the foundation of the Disaster Response & Rescue Navigation System. The efficiency of the application depends on selecting appropriate Data Structures and Algorithms capable of processing road networks, identifying emergency facilities, and computing optimal rescue routes within minimum time.\par
\fi720 the proposed system represents the transportation network as a weighted graph. Each location is considered a vertex, while roads connecting two locations are represented as weighted edges. The graph enables efficient implementation of shortest path and graph traversal algorithms.\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.2 Graph Data Structure\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 A graph is a non-linear data structure consisting of a collection of vertices (nodes) connected by edges. Graphs are widely used for representing transportation networks because roads naturally form interconnected paths between different locations. In this project, cities are represented as vertices, roads are represented as weighted edges, and edge weights correspond to the distance between two connected locations.\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.3 Graph Representation in the Project\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The transportation network is stored using an Adjacency List. Each city maintains a list of neighbouring cities along with the distance between them. In C++, the graph is represented using vectors and pairs, allowing efficient storage of neighbouring nodes and corresponding weights. Adjacency lists require less memory and support faster traversal of neighbouring nodes compared to adjacency matrices.\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.4 Dijkstra's Algorithm\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 Dijkstra's Algorithm computes the minimum distance between a source vertex and all other vertices in a weighted graph containing non-negative edge weights. Within this project, Dijkstra's Algorithm is responsible for determining the optimal rescue route. The algorithm begins by assigning a distance value of zero to the source vertex and infinity to all remaining vertices. It repeatedly selects the unvisited vertex with the minimum tentative distance using a priority queue, visits neighbours, updates distances if a shorter path is found, and reconstructs the path.\par
\qc
\f1 Dijkstra's Algorithm Pseudocode:\f0\par
\qj
\f0\fs20
\tab Initialize distance[source] = 0\par
\tab For every other vertex distance = Infinity\par
\tab Insert source into Priority Queue\par
\tab While Priority Queue is not empty:\par
\tab     Remove minimum distance vertex u\par
\tab     For each neighbour v of u:\par
\tab         If distance[u] + weight(u,v) < distance[v]:\par
\tab             Update distance[v]\par
\tab             Update parent[v] = u\par
\tab             Insert v into Priority Queue\par
\tab Return shortest path\par
\fs24\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.5 Breadth-First Search (BFS)\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 Breadth-First Search (BFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores all neighbouring vertices of the current node before moving to the next level of the graph. It follows a level-by-level approach and uses a Queue data structure to maintain the order of traversal. In disaster management, BFS is useful to explore all locations that are directly reachable from a particular city to analyze connectivity.\par
\qc
\f1 BFS Pseudocode:\f0\par
\qj
\f0\fs20
\tab Create an empty Queue\par
\tab Mark source as visited\par
\tab Push source into Queue\par
\tab While Queue is not empty:\par
\tab     Remove front vertex u\par
\tab     Visit the vertex u\par
\tab     For every neighbour v of u:\par
\tab         If v is not visited:\par
\tab             Mark v as visited\par
\tab             Push v into Queue\par
\fs24\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.6 Depth-First Search (DFS)\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 Depth-First Search (DFS) explores one branch of the graph as deeply as possible before backtracking to visit remaining branches. It uses a Stack or recursion to manage traversal. DFS is useful for analyzing connectivity, detecting connected components, and understanding network structures.\par
\qc
\f1 DFS Pseudocode:\f0\par
\qj
\f0\fs20
\tab DFS(vertex):\par
\tab Mark vertex as visited\par
\tab Visit vertex\par
\tab For every neighbour v of vertex:\par
\tab     If v is not visited:\par
\tab         DFS(v)\par
\fs24\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.7 Priority Queue\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 A Priority Queue is a specialized data structure that always removes the element with the highest priority. In this project, the priority is based on the minimum distance, making a min-priority queue ideal for Dijkstra's Algorithm. Insertions and deletions run in O(log V) time using heap structures, improving pathfinding speed.\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.8 Complexity Analysis\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The overall computational complexity of the major algorithms is summarized below:\par
\qc
\b Complexity Table\b0\par
\tab \b Algorithm \b0\tab\tab\tab \b Time Complexity \b0\tab \b Space Complexity\b0\par
\tab Graph Construction\tab\tab O(V + E)\tab\tab O(V + E)\par
\tab Dijkstra's Algorithm\tab\tab O((V + E) log V)\tab O(V + E)\par
\tab Breadth-First Search\tab\tab O(V + E)\tab\tab O(V)\par
\tab Depth-First Search\tab\tab O(V + E)\tab\tab O(V)\par
\qj\par

\f1\fs28\b 4.9 Summary\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The algorithms enable efficient route planning, reduce computational overhead, and provide a strong foundation for disaster response applications. The algorithmic approach adopted highlights how theoretical DSA concepts can be applied to practical engineering problems.\par
