\f1\fs28\b 5.6 Performance Analysis\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The use of an adjacency list minimizes memory usage, while the priority queue enables efficient execution of Dijkstra's Algorithm. BFS and DFS execute in linear time, providing instant calculations for the 41-city network.\par

\f1\fs28\b 5.7 Advantages Observed During Testing\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 Testing confirmed fast path calculations, correct graph constructions, accurate overlays of nearby resources, and responsive UI dashboard interactions.\par

\f1\fs28\b 5.8 Discussion\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The implementation demonstrates that graph-based algorithms are highly effective for disaster response. The separation of routing logic from the user interface improves maintainability and makes the application easy to extend.\par
\page

\f1\fs32\b CHAPTER 6\par\par
CONCLUSION\b0\fs24\f0\par\par
\f1\fs28\b 6.1 Conclusion\b0\fs24\f0\par
\fi720 The Disaster Response & Rescue Navigation System was developed to demonstrate the practical application of Data Structures and Algorithms in emergency route planning. By implementing Dijkstra's Algorithm, the system determines the shortest path between locations, enabling rescue teams to reach affected areas efficiently. BFS and DFS support connectivity analysis, and the priority queue improves the performance of shortest-path computation.\par
\fi720 The project successfully meets its primary objectives: implementation of graph-based emergency navigation, shortest-path computations, connectivity traversing, and dashboard resource coordination. The implementation confirms that graph algorithms provide an effective solution for emergency route planning.\par

